const Q = [
  // DOMAIN 1 (23 questions)
  {d:1,q:"A developer needs to build a RAG system that retrieves relevant documents and generates answers. Which Amazon Bedrock feature provides managed document ingestion, chunking, embedding, and retrieval in a single service?",o:["Amazon Bedrock Agents","Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases","Amazon Bedrock Prompt Management","Amazon Bedrock Guardrails"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases is the fully managed RAG service — it handles ingestion, chunking, embedding, indexing, and retrieval without custom infrastructure code.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Agents automates multi-step tasks but is not a document ingestion pipeline.<br>C — Prompt Management versions prompt templates and has no document ingestion capability.<br>D — Guardrails applies safety filters to inputs and outputs; it does not manage documents."},
  {d:1,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock embedding model supports configurable output dimensions of 256, 512, and 1024?",o:["Amazon Titan Text G1","Amazon Titan Multimodal Embeddings G1","Amazon Titan Text Embeddings V2","Cohere Embed English"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Titan Text Embeddings V2 is the only Bedrock embedding model that lets you choose the output dimension (256, 512, or 1024), balancing accuracy vs. storage cost.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Titan Text G1 is a generation model, not an embedding model.<br>B — Titan Multimodal Embeddings supports images and text but uses fixed dimensions (384 or 1024).<br>D — Cohere Embed English is not a variable-dimension model in Bedrock."},
  {d:1,q:"A company needs a pgvector index for 500,000 documents requiring the best balance of recall accuracy and query speed. Which index type should they choose?",o:["Flat (no index)","IVFFlat","HNSW","BTree"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> HNSW provides the best recall-to-speed tradeoff for corpora in the 10K–1M range. It builds a graph structure at index time and navigates it at query time with sub-linear complexity.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Flat is exact but O(n) — impractical for 500K documents at scale.<br>B — IVFFlat suits very large datasets but requires a training phase and has lower recall than HNSW at equal speed.<br>D — BTree is for scalar values, not vector similarity search."},
  {d:1,q:"Which pgvector operator computes cosine distance between two normalised embedding vectors?",o:["<->","<#>","<=>","@@"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> The <code>&lt;=&gt;</code> operator computes cosine distance. For normalised vectors (Titan Embeddings V2 with normalize:true), cosine distance equals 1 minus cosine similarity. Order ascending for most similar results first.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — <code>&lt;-&gt;</code> computes Euclidean (L2) distance for unnormalised vectors.<br>B — <code>&lt;#&gt;</code> computes negative inner product for maximising dot product similarity.<br>D — <code>@@</code> is a PostgreSQL full-text search operator, unrelated to vector search."},
  {d:1,q:"What is the default chunking configuration used by Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases when no custom strategy is specified?",o:["200 tokens with 10% overlap","300 tokens with 20% overlap","512 tokens with 10% overlap","800 tokens with 15% overlap"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Bedrock Knowledge Bases uses 300 tokens with 20% overlap as its default chunking strategy. Critical exam fact: you cannot change the chunking strategy after creating a data source — you must recreate it.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A, C, D — None of these match the AWS-documented defaults for Bedrock Knowledge Bases."},
  {d:1,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases vector store supports hybrid search combining both vector similarity and keyword search?",o:["Amazon S3 Vectors","Amazon Aurora (pgvector)","Amazon MemoryDB","Amazon OpenSearch Serverless"],a:3,e:"<span class='why-correct'>D is correct.</span> Amazon OpenSearch Serverless natively supports hybrid search — combining dense vector similarity with sparse BM25 keyword search. It is the recommended choice for large-scale RAG where keyword precision matters.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — S3 Vectors is a new low-cost vector store but supports only vector search.<br>B — Aurora pgvector can do keyword search with separate SQL but not natively through the Bedrock KB interface.<br>C — MemoryDB has vector capabilities but does not provide hybrid search in the Bedrock KB context."},
  {d:1,q:"A developer embeds documents using Titan Text Embeddings V2 with normalize:true. What similarity metric should they use?",o:["Euclidean distance (L2)","Manhattan distance","Cosine similarity","Negative inner product"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> For unit-normalised embeddings, cosine similarity is the correct metric. For normalised vectors, cosine similarity equals the dot product, making the <code>&lt;=&gt;</code> pgvector operator the right choice.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Euclidean distance suits unnormalised vectors where magnitude carries meaning.<br>B — Manhattan distance is not used for embedding similarity search.<br>D — Negative inner product is less intuitive than cosine for normalised embeddings."},
  {d:1,q:"A developer in eu-west-2 tries to invoke the Claude Haiku 4.5 cross-region inference profile for the first time and receives an access error. Which IAM permission is missing?",o:["bedrock:InvokeModel","aws-marketplace:Subscribe","bedrock:CreateModelInvocationJob","iam:PassRole"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Cross-region inference profiles (identified by the eu. or us. prefix) require the invoking principal to have <code>aws-marketplace:Subscribe</code> for the first invocation in an AWS account.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — bedrock:InvokeModel is required but alone is insufficient for first-time cross-region profile access.<br>C — CreateModelInvocationJob is for batch inference, not real-time invocation.<br>D — iam:PassRole is needed when creating service roles, not for model invocation."},
  {d:1,q:"A company needs to update their customer support chatbot with the latest product specifications daily. Which approach is most appropriate?",o:["Fine-tune the foundation model weekly with updated product data","Use RAG with a daily document ingestion pipeline","Hard-code product information into the system prompt","Use distillation to create a smaller model trained on product data"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> RAG is ideal for frequently updated information — you refresh the document store without retraining the model. Daily ingestion pipelines keep knowledge current at low cost.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Weekly fine-tuning is expensive, slow to deploy, and requires full retraining whenever data changes.<br>C — System prompts have limited context window space and cannot hold a full product catalogue.<br>D — Distillation creates a smaller model from a larger model's outputs — not a mechanism for live data updates."},
  {d:1,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases API performs both retrieval and generation in a single API call?",o:["Retrieve","InvokeModel","RetrieveAndGenerate","Converse"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> RetrieveAndGenerate is the end-to-end RAG API. It takes a query, retrieves relevant chunks from the knowledge base, and generates a grounded response — all in one call.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Retrieve returns chunks only. You handle generation yourself using InvokeModel — useful for custom prompting, model selection, or Guardrails integration.<br>B — InvokeModel calls a foundation model directly with your prompt. No knowledge base integration.<br>D — Converse is a multi-turn conversation API for direct model invocation, not for Knowledge Bases."},
  {d:1,q:"A developer uses a cross-region inference profile ARN (eu.anthropic.claude-*) as the model for RetrieveAndGenerate and receives a ValidationException. What is the cause?",o:["The model is not available in the specified region","RetrieveAndGenerate only accepts direct foundation model ARNs, not cross-region inference profile IDs","The Knowledge Base is not synced","The IAM role lacks bedrock:InvokeModel permission"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> RetrieveAndGenerate validates the model ARN and rejects cross-region inference profile IDs (eu. or us. prefix). You must use a direct foundation model ARN in the format <code>arn:aws:bedrock:REGION::foundation-model/MODEL_ID</code>.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — The model is available; the issue is the ARN format.<br>C — Knowledge Base sync status affects retrieval, not model validation.<br>D — IAM permission errors return AccessDeniedException, not ValidationException."},
  {d:1,q:"A developer uses Titan Text Embeddings V2 with normalize:true. What mathematical effect does normalisation have?",o:["Reduces the vector dimensions by 50%","Makes all vector components positive","Scales the vector to unit length so cosine similarity equals the dot product","Removes dimensions with values close to zero"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Normalising to unit length (magnitude = 1) makes cosine similarity equivalent to the dot product between two vectors. This simplifies similarity computation and makes HNSW queries more efficient.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Normalisation does not change the number of dimensions.<br>B — Normalisation adjusts magnitude, not sign. Components can remain negative.<br>D — Normalisation is a scaling operation only; it does not drop dimensions."},
  {d:1,q:"A company needs to store and search 10 million document vectors with full-text keyword search alongside vector search. Which vector store should they choose?",o:["Amazon Aurora (pgvector)","Amazon S3 Vectors","Amazon OpenSearch Serverless","Amazon DynamoDB"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> OpenSearch Serverless supports both vector similarity and full-text keyword search natively. It scales to billions of vectors and its hybrid search capability is specifically recommended by AWS for large-scale RAG workloads.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Aurora pgvector is excellent for up to a few million vectors but lacks native hybrid search through Bedrock KBs.<br>B — S3 Vectors is a low-cost option but does not provide hybrid search.<br>D — DynamoDB is a key-value store; it does not support vector similarity search."},
  {d:1,q:"Which chunking strategy identifies topic shifts in text and splits at semantic boundaries rather than at fixed token counts?",o:["Fixed-size chunking","Recursive character chunking","Semantic chunking","Sentence chunking"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Semantic chunking uses embedding similarity to detect where the meaning shifts, then splits at those boundaries. This produces topically coherent chunks that improve retrieval accuracy — at higher computational cost.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Fixed-size splits at a fixed number of tokens regardless of content boundaries.<br>B — Recursive character chunking splits by paragraphs, sentences, then characters — not by semantic meaning.<br>D — Sentence chunking splits at sentence boundaries but does not group related sentences together."},
  {d:1,q:"A company is deciding between RAG and fine-tuning for a use case requiring a frequently updated internal knowledge base of 50,000 documents. Which approach is correct?",o:["Fine-tuning, because it embeds knowledge directly into model weights","RAG, because it retrieves current information without requiring retraining","Fine-tuning, because it produces lower latency at inference time","Both are equally suitable"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> RAG is the correct choice when: (1) the knowledge base is large, (2) it changes frequently, and (3) auditability matters. Fine-tuning embeds knowledge into weights at training time — expensive, slow to update, and not suitable for dynamic information.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Fine-tuning would require full retraining every time the knowledge base changes.<br>C — Fine-tuned models have similar inference latency to base models; this is not the key differentiator.<br>D — They are not equally suitable. RAG is clearly superior for large, dynamic knowledge bases."},
  {d:1,q:"After creating a Bedrock Knowledge Bases data source with a custom chunking strategy, a developer wants to change the chunk size. What must they do?",o:["Edit the data source chunking configuration and resync","Delete and recreate the data source with the new chunking strategy","Update the embedding model to trigger rechunking","Change the chunk size in the Bedrock console without any other action"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> The chunking strategy cannot be modified after creating a data source. To change it, delete the data source, recreate it with the desired configuration, then resync the documents.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — There is no edit option for chunking on an existing data source.<br>C — The embedding model does not control chunking.<br>D — The console does not allow changing chunk size on an existing data source."},
  {d:1,q:"A developer is using Titan Text Embeddings V2 for RAG. Which input type should they use when embedding the user's search query?",o:["search_document","search_query","clustering","classification"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Titan Text Embeddings V2 supports different input types. Use <code>search_query</code> for the user's question and <code>search_document</code> for documents during ingestion. This asymmetric embedding improves retrieval quality.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — search_document is used for the documents being indexed, not for the query.<br>C — clustering is used for grouping similar documents, not search.<br>D — classification is used for text classification tasks, not retrieval."},
  {d:1,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock feature lets a single application call different foundation models for different tasks?",o:["Bedrock Agents action groups","Foundation model IDs in InvokeModel calls","Bedrock Guardrails per-model configuration","Bedrock Prompt Management model binding"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Each InvokeModel call specifies a modelId. A single application can use <code>amazon.titan-embed-text-v2:0</code> for embeddings and <code>eu.anthropic.claude-haiku-4-5-20251001-v1:0</code> for generation by simply specifying the appropriate modelId in each call.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Agents action groups define tools; they don't select models per task.<br>C — Guardrails are safety filters, not model selectors.<br>D — Prompt Management templates can be bound to a model but are not the primary mechanism for multi-model applications."},
  {d:1,q:"A developer is building a multimodal RAG system where users can search using both images and text. Which Amazon Bedrock embedding model should they use?",o:["Titan Text Embeddings V2 with 1024 dimensions","Titan Multimodal Embeddings G1","Cohere Embed English","Titan Text G1"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Titan Multimodal Embeddings G1 supports both image and text inputs, generating embeddings in a shared vector space. This allows cross-modal similarity — finding images similar to a text query or vice versa.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Titan Text Embeddings V2 only embeds text; it cannot process images.<br>C — Cohere Embed English handles text only.<br>D — Titan Text G1 is a text generation model, not an embedding model."},
  {d:1,q:"What is the key difference between using Retrieve versus RetrieveAndGenerate in Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases?",o:["Retrieve uses keyword search; RetrieveAndGenerate uses vector search","Retrieve returns raw chunks with scores for custom generation; RetrieveAndGenerate handles both retrieval and generation in one call","Retrieve supports more models than RetrieveAndGenerate","RetrieveAndGenerate supports cross-region inference profiles but Retrieve does not"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Retrieve returns document chunks with similarity scores, giving you full control over generation. RetrieveAndGenerate does both steps in one call with less control. Use Retrieve when you need custom generation, Guardrails integration, or prompt versioning.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Both APIs use vector search; the difference is what happens after retrieval.<br>C — RetrieveAndGenerate restricts model selection; Retrieve + custom InvokeModel gives more options.<br>D — RetrieveAndGenerate rejects cross-region inference profiles; this statement is the opposite of reality."},
  {d:1,q:"A Lambda function in a private VPC must call Bedrock for embeddings and query a Knowledge Base. No internet access. Which VPC endpoints are required?",o:["bedrock-runtime only","bedrock-runtime and bedrock-agent-runtime","bedrock-agent and bedrock-agent-runtime","bedrock-runtime, bedrock-agent, and bedrock-agent-runtime"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> You need: <code>bedrock-runtime</code> for InvokeModel (embeddings and generation) and <code>bedrock-agent-runtime</code> for RetrieveAndGenerate or Retrieve (Knowledge Bases). If you also use Prompt Management (GetPrompt), you additionally need <code>bedrock-agent</code>.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — bedrock-runtime alone cannot reach Knowledge Bases APIs.<br>C — Missing InvokeModel for embeddings.<br>D — Three endpoints are needed only when also using Prompt Management."},
  {d:1,q:"A company fine-tunes a foundation model on domain-specific data and notices it performs significantly worse on general tasks. What is this phenomenon called?",o:["Data poisoning","Catastrophic forgetting","Model collapse","Overfitting"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Catastrophic forgetting occurs when fine-tuning on new data causes the model to lose performance on previously learned tasks. This is a key reason why RAG is often preferred over fine-tuning for domain-specific knowledge.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Data poisoning involves malicious training data, not a natural consequence of fine-tuning.<br>C — Model collapse refers to a generative model losing diversity after training on synthetic data.<br>D — Overfitting is performing well on training data but poorly on new data within the same domain."},
  {d:1,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases vector store is the most cost-effective for a low-traffic RAG system where minimising infrastructure cost is the priority?",o:["Amazon Aurora (pgvector) Serverless v2","Amazon OpenSearch Serverless","Amazon S3 Vectors","Amazon MemoryDB"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Amazon S3 Vectors is the lowest-cost vector store option for Bedrock Knowledge Bases — no cluster to manage and no per-hour charges, making it ideal for development, low-traffic, or cost-sensitive workloads.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Aurora Serverless v2 has per-ACU-hour charges — more expensive than S3 Vectors for low-traffic workloads.<br>B — OpenSearch Serverless has minimum OCU charges of approximately $350/month — by far the most expensive option.<br>D — MemoryDB is an in-memory store with per-hour node pricing."},

  // DOMAIN 2 (20 questions)
  {d:2,q:"A developer wants the model to explain its step-by-step reasoning before producing a final answer. Which prompt engineering technique achieves this?",o:["Zero-shot prompting","Few-shot prompting","Chain-of-thought prompting","Role prompting"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Chain-of-thought (CoT) prompting asks the model to show its reasoning steps before answering. This significantly improves performance on math, logic, and multi-step reasoning tasks.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Zero-shot gives only the task description with no reasoning guidance.<br>B — Few-shot provides example input-output pairs, helping with format but not requesting reasoning steps.<br>D — Role prompting sets a persona for the model but does not dictate reasoning structure."},
  {d:2,q:"A company wants to update the system prompt for their AI assistant without redeploying Lambda or changing application code. Which Amazon Bedrock feature enables this?",o:["Bedrock Agents","Bedrock Prompt Management","Bedrock Guardrails","Bedrock Knowledge Bases"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Bedrock Prompt Management stores versioned prompt templates. Lambda fetches the template via GetPrompt at runtime (cached with lru_cache). To update the prompt, create a new version and update the PROMPT_ARN environment variable — no Lambda redeployment needed.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Bedrock Agents orchestrates multi-step tasks but is not a prompt versioning service.<br>C — Guardrails applies content filters; it does not manage prompt templates.<br>D — Knowledge Bases manages document storage and retrieval; it does not version prompts."},
  {d:2,q:"In Amazon Bedrock Prompt Management, what syntax is used to define variables within a prompt template?",o:["{single_braces}","{{double_braces}}","$variable","<variable>"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Bedrock Prompt Management uses <code>{{double_braces}}</code> for variable substitution. For example, <code>{{context}}</code> and <code>{{question}}</code> are replaced at runtime with values passed in the API call.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Single braces are used in Python f-strings but not in Bedrock Prompt Management.<br>C — Dollar sign variables are used in Bash and some template engines but not in Bedrock.<br>D — XML-style tags are not used for Bedrock Prompt Management variables."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer creates a RAG prompt template using the Bedrock console Prompt Management builder. Their Lambda code parses templateConfiguration.chat.messages. Why specifically chat messages?",o:["The developer has a bug and should use templateConfiguration.text","The Bedrock console creates CHAT-type prompts by default, not TEXT-type","All Bedrock prompts use the chat message format regardless of creation method","The Lambda handler is receiving the wrong API response"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> When you create a prompt using the Bedrock console, it creates a CHAT-type prompt with system instructions and message turns, stored as <code>templateConfiguration.chat</code>. Programmatically created plain text templates are TEXT-type stored under <code>templateConfiguration.text</code>. Lambda code must handle both types.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — The code is correct; console-created prompts do use the chat structure.<br>C — Prompts can be either TEXT or CHAT type depending on how they were created.<br>D — The API response format is correct."},
  {d:2,q:"Which Amazon API Gateway type natively supports JWT authorizers with Amazon Cognito, costs ~70% less per million API calls, and uses payload format version 2.0?",o:["REST API","WebSocket API","HTTP API","GraphQL API"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> HTTP API is the modern, lightweight option. It supports JWT authorizers natively, costs ~70% less than REST API, and uses payload format 2.0 which simplifies the Lambda event and response structure.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — REST API is more expensive and requires a custom Lambda authorizer for JWT validation.<br>B — WebSocket API is for real-time bidirectional connections, not standard REST-style RAG endpoints.<br>D — Amazon does not offer a native GraphQL API Gateway product."},
  {d:2,q:"A chatbot application runs on AWS Lambda and needs to remember the last 5 conversation turns across invocations. Which service should store the session history?",o:["Amazon S3","Amazon ElastiCache for Redis","Amazon DynamoDB","Lambda ephemeral storage (/tmp)"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> DynamoDB is the standard choice for Lambda session storage: serverless, millisecond reads, TTL for automatic expiry, and efficient queries by session_id + timestamp for the most recent N turns.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — S3 is object storage; reading recent conversation history requires listing and downloading objects — too slow.<br>B — ElastiCache works but requires VPC placement and ongoing cluster cost — more operational overhead than DynamoDB.<br>D — Lambda /tmp is local to a single invocation and not shared across concurrent invocations or persisted."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer sets the temperature parameter to 0.0 when calling a Claude model via Amazon Bedrock InvokeModel. What behaviour should they expect?",o:["The model refuses to generate a response","The model produces fully random, highly creative output","The model produces deterministic, most-probable output","The model generates shorter responses"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Temperature controls randomness of token selection. At 0, the model always selects the most probable next token — deterministic and focused. At 1, the distribution is unchanged. Above 1, output becomes increasingly random.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Temperature 0 does not cause refusal; it makes the model more focused.<br>B — Temperature 0 is the opposite of random; high temperature produces random output.<br>D — Temperature does not control response length; max_tokens controls that."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer wants to display AI-generated text in real time, character by character, as it is being generated. Which Amazon Bedrock API should they call?",o:["InvokeModel","InvokeModelWithResponseStream","Converse","RetrieveAndGenerate"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> InvokeModelWithResponseStream returns the model's response as a stream of chunks. The client receives each token as it is generated, enabling real-time display and a much better user experience.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — InvokeModel waits for the complete response before returning. The user sees nothing until generation is complete.<br>C — Converse supports streaming via ConverseStream, but InvokeModelWithResponseStream is the standard streaming API.<br>D — RetrieveAndGenerate is for Knowledge Base queries and does not natively support streaming in all configurations."},
  {d:2,q:"Which Amazon Cognito component authenticates users and issues JWT access tokens, ID tokens, and refresh tokens for API Gateway JWT authorizers?",o:["Identity Pool","User Pool","Federated Identity","SAML provider"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Cognito User Pools handle user registration, authentication, and token issuance. After sign-in, users receive an ID token, access token, and refresh token. The API Gateway JWT authorizer validates these against the User Pool.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Identity Pools exchange authenticated identities for temporary AWS IAM credentials — used when apps need to call AWS services directly, not for API Gateway JWT auth.<br>C — Federated Identity is a concept used by Identity Pools for social/enterprise login federation.<br>D — SAML providers are external identity sources federated into Cognito, not a Cognito component itself."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer runs aws cognito-idp initiate-auth with USER_PASSWORD_AUTH and receives: NotAuthorizedException: Client configured with secret but SECRET_HASH was not received. What is the root cause?",o:["The user's password is incorrect","The Cognito app client was created as a confidential client with a client secret","USER_PASSWORD_AUTH is disabled for this user pool","The user has not confirmed their account"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> When a Cognito app client has a client secret, every authentication request must include a SECRET_HASH — an HMAC-SHA256 signature. The standard CLI command does not compute this. Fix: create a new public app client with the client secret toggle disabled.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Incorrect password returns 'Incorrect username or password', not a SECRET_HASH error.<br>C — USER_PASSWORD_AUTH being disabled returns a different error.<br>D — Unconfirmed users return 'User is not confirmed'."},
  {d:2,q:"A Lambda function in a private subnet with no NAT Gateway calls InvokeModel and experiences timeout errors. Which VPC endpoint is required?",o:["com.amazonaws.eu-west-2.bedrock-agent","com.amazonaws.eu-west-2.bedrock-agent-runtime","com.amazonaws.eu-west-2.bedrock-runtime","com.amazonaws.eu-west-2.bedrock"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> The <code>bedrock-runtime</code> VPC interface endpoint enables InvokeModel and InvokeModelWithResponseStream from a private VPC. Without it, calls silently hang until the Lambda timeout.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — bedrock-agent enables GetPrompt (Prompt Management) and Bedrock Agents APIs, not InvokeModel.<br>B — bedrock-agent-runtime enables Knowledge Base APIs (Retrieve, RetrieveAndGenerate), not InvokeModel.<br>D — There is no VPC endpoint service named simply 'bedrock'."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer wants to build an AI system that can browse the web, query a database, send emails, and repeat over multiple steps to complete complex tasks. Which Amazon Bedrock feature is most appropriate?",o:["Bedrock Knowledge Bases","Bedrock Prompt Management","Bedrock Guardrails","Bedrock Agents"],a:3,e:"<span class='why-correct'>D is correct.</span> Bedrock Agents orchestrates multi-step workflows where the model decides which tools (action groups) to call, in what order, based on the current task state. It maintains context across steps and can call external APIs, query databases, and take actions autonomously.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Knowledge Bases handles document retrieval, not multi-step tool orchestration.<br>B — Prompt Management stores versioned prompts; it does not execute workflows.<br>C — Guardrails applies content safety filters; it does not orchestrate actions."},
  {d:2,q:"An API must support monetisation through per-customer rate limiting and API key-based access control. Which API Gateway feature provides this?",o:["HTTP API with JWT authorizer","REST API with usage plans and API keys","HTTP API with IAM authorization","WebSocket API with connection management"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> REST API with usage plans is the AWS-native approach for API key management and rate limiting. Usage plans define throttle and quota limits; API keys are associated with usage plans for per-customer billing and rate limiting.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — HTTP API supports JWT auth but does not have native API key management or usage plans.<br>C — IAM auth for HTTP API is for internal AWS service-to-service calls, not customer-facing API key distribution.<br>D — WebSocket API is for real-time connections, not REST-style API key management."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer receives ContentBlock is blank error when testing a prompt in Amazon Bedrock Prompt Management. They have no empty variables. What is the most likely cause?",o:["The context variable contains too much text","The prompt template is missing required variables","An empty Assistant message field was left in the prompt builder","The selected model does not support chat-type prompts"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> The Bedrock console Prompt Management builder shows an optional Assistant message field below the User message. If left empty but included in the CHAT-type prompt structure, Bedrock returns ContentBlock is blank. The fix: click the trash icon to remove the empty Assistant message field.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Overly long context causes token limit errors, not ContentBlock validation errors.<br>B — Missing required variables produce a VariableError, not ContentBlock is blank.<br>D — The model does support CHAT-type prompts; the issue is the empty Assistant message field."},
  {d:2,q:"A Lambda function needs to call Amazon Bedrock and read documents from S3. Which IAM configuration follows the principle of least privilege?",o:["Attach AdministratorAccess to the Lambda execution role","Create a specific IAM role with bedrock:InvokeModel on required models and s3:GetObject on the specific bucket","Use the root account credentials in Lambda environment variables","Share an IAM role with administrator permissions across all Lambda functions"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Least privilege means granting only the specific permissions required. Create a Lambda execution role with bedrock:InvokeModel scoped to needed model ARNs and s3:GetObject scoped to the specific S3 bucket — nothing broader.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — AdministratorAccess grants all permissions to all resources — the opposite of least privilege.<br>C — Root credentials in environment variables is a critical security violation; credentials can be extracted from Lambda configuration.<br>D — Sharing administrator roles across functions means a compromise of one function exposes all others."},
  {d:2,q:"A company wants a complete audit trail showing exactly which prompt version generated each response. How should they implement this?",o:["Log all prompts to CloudWatch manually","Use Bedrock Prompt Management and include the versioned prompt ARN in every API response","Store prompts in DynamoDB with a version counter","Use AWS CloudTrail to track all Bedrock API calls"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Bedrock Prompt Management versions prompts with immutable ARNs in the format <code>arn:aws:bedrock:REGION:ACCOUNT:prompt/ID:VERSION</code>. Returning this ARN in every API response makes every answer traceable to an exact prompt version — a key governance capability for production AI systems.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Manual CloudWatch logging requires custom code and is error-prone.<br>C — A custom DynamoDB version counter works but is non-standard and harder to audit than Bedrock's native versioning.<br>D — CloudTrail records API calls but does not directly associate prompt versions with generated responses."},
  {d:2,q:"An AWS Lambda function processing complex AI queries consistently takes between 12 and 14 minutes. What is the maximum timeout the developer can configure?",o:["5 minutes","10 minutes","15 minutes","30 minutes"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> AWS Lambda has a hard maximum timeout of 15 minutes (900 seconds). For workloads that regularly approach this limit, consider Step Functions for orchestration or ECS/Fargate for long-running tasks.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — 5 minutes is the recommended timeout for many RAG queries but not the maximum.<br>B — 10 minutes is a common middle ground but not the maximum Lambda supports.<br>D — 30 minutes exceeds Lambda's hard limit and is not a valid configuration."},
  {d:2,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock API natively manages multi-turn conversation history with a consistent interface across Claude models?",o:["InvokeModel","Converse","InvokeModelWithResponseStream","RetrieveAndGenerate"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> The Converse API has a native multi-turn conversation design — you pass the full conversation history as a messages array and it returns the next assistant turn. It provides a consistent interface across Claude models, abstracting model-specific prompt formats.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — InvokeModel requires you to format the complete prompt yourself, including conversation history, in the model-specific format.<br>C — InvokeModelWithResponseStream is the streaming version of InvokeModel; same prompt formatting requirements.<br>D — RetrieveAndGenerate is for Knowledge Base queries; it is not a general multi-turn conversation API."},
  {d:2,q:"Which LangChain package provides official support for using Amazon Bedrock models in LangChain applications?",o:["openai with custom API endpoint","langchain-aws with ChatBedrock or BedrockLLM","LangChain does not support Amazon Bedrock","Custom AmazonBedrock wrapper class"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> The <code>langchain-aws</code> package provides <code>ChatBedrock</code> (for chat models like Claude) and <code>BedrockLLM</code> (for completion models) as first-class integrations implementing the standard LangChain LLM interface.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Using the OpenAI adapter requires a compatibility shim and is not the recommended approach.<br>C — LangChain has extensive native support for Amazon Bedrock through the langchain-aws package.<br>D — There is no separate AmazonBedrock custom wrapper class required."},
  {d:2,q:"What does few-shot prompting involve?",o:["Providing zero examples and relying on the model's general knowledge","Providing 2-10 example input-output pairs in the prompt to guide the model's response format","Fine-tuning the model on a few hundred labelled examples","Using a smaller model to generate training data for a larger model"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Few-shot prompting includes a small number (typically 2-10) of example input-output pairs directly in the prompt context. This helps the model understand the desired output format, tone, and task without any training.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — That describes zero-shot prompting, where no examples are provided.<br>C — That describes fine-tuning, which involves actual model weight updates using a training dataset.<br>D — That describes knowledge distillation."},
  {d:2,q:"A developer is building a web application requiring user authentication with tokens expiring after 60 minutes. Which AWS architecture is most appropriate?",o:["API Gateway with IAM authorization and SigV4 signing from the client","API Gateway HTTP API with Cognito User Pool JWT authorizer","Expose the Lambda function URL directly with IAM auth","Implement custom authentication logic inside the Lambda function"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> API Gateway HTTP API with a Cognito JWT authorizer is the standard pattern for web application authentication. Users authenticate with Cognito (60-minute token expiry is configurable), receive JWT tokens, and include the bearer token in API requests. API Gateway validates the token without invoking Lambda for auth.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — IAM authorization with SigV4 requires clients to have AWS credentials and perform cryptographic signing — not suitable for end users.<br>C — Lambda function URLs can use IAM auth but are not designed for end-user authentication or JWT support.<br>D — Custom auth in Lambda bypasses API Gateway's built-in JWT validation, adding latency and complexity."},

  // DOMAIN 3 (15 questions)
  {d:3,q:"A financial services company wants to prevent their AI chatbot from providing investment advice. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails configuration should they use?",o:["Content filters with Financial set to High","Sensitive information filters for financial data","Denied topics with definition and example phrases for financial advice","Contextual grounding with threshold 0.9"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Denied topics let you define specific subjects the model should refuse to discuss, along with a plain-language definition and example phrases. Guardrails detects and blocks queries related to the denied topic, even when phrased differently from the examples.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Content filters apply to hate, violence, sexual content, etc. There is no 'Financial' content filter category.<br>B — Sensitive information filters detect and mask/block specific data types like credit card numbers and SSNs, not entire conversation topics.<br>D — Contextual grounding checks if the model's answer is supported by retrieved context, not whether the topic is allowed."},
  {d:3,q:"Bedrock Guardrails contextual grounding is set to threshold 0.75. A query returns an answer scoring 0.60 for grounding. What happens?",o:["The answer is returned normally with a warning","The answer is blocked and a substituted message is returned","The answer is returned with a lower confidence score","The query is retried with a different model"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> The contextual grounding filter compares the answer against retrieved context. If the grounding score is below the configured threshold (0.60 < 0.75), the Guardrail blocks the response and substitutes it with the configured blocked message or the Bedrock default.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Guardrails do not return partial answers with warnings; they either pass or block.<br>C — There is no concept of returning an answer with a lower confidence score from Guardrails.<br>D — Guardrails do not trigger query retries."},
  {d:3,q:"Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails content filter category should be set to High to protect against users trying to override system instructions?",o:["Hate","Violence","Prompt Attack","Sexual"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Prompt Attack is the Guardrails filter specifically designed to detect and block prompt injection attempts — both direct (user input) and indirect (via retrieved documents). Setting it to High provides the most aggressive protection against jailbreak and instruction-override attempts.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Hate filters hateful speech; it does not protect against system prompt extraction.<br>B — Violence filters content depicting physical harm; it does not detect instruction override attempts.<br>D — Sexual filters explicit content; it does not detect prompt injection techniques."},
  {d:3,q:"A Bedrock Guardrail triggers and stop_reason in the API response is guardrail_intervened. What type of intervention is this?",o:["Message substitution — response replaced with a safe message, HTTP 200 returned","Hard block — generation stopped with stop_reason set to guardrail_intervened","Warning — response is flagged but still returned","Retry — request resent to a different model"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> When stop_reason is <code>guardrail_intervened</code>, the Guardrail has performed a hard block — generation was stopped and the response body includes <code>amazon-bedrock-guardrailAction</code>. Message substitution, by contrast, returns HTTP 200 with stop_reason of end_turn and a replacement message that looks like a normal response.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Message substitution returns HTTP 200 and stop_reason of end_turn, not guardrail_intervened.<br>C — Guardrails do not have a warning mode; they either block or pass.<br>D — Guardrails do not trigger automatic retries."},
  {d:3,q:"A RAG system processes documents that may contain email addresses and phone numbers. The company wants these masked in responses but not blocked entirely. Which Guardrails configuration is correct?",o:["Set email and phone to Block in sensitive information filters","Set email and phone to Mask in sensitive information filters","Add email and phone as denied topics","Use content filters with Privacy set to High"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Sensitive information filters in Bedrock Guardrails support Mask (replaces with a redacted placeholder like [EMAIL]) and Block (blocks the entire response) per PII type. For compliance while preserving usability, Mask is appropriate for contact information.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Blocking email and phone entirely would prevent many legitimate responses from being returned.<br>C — Denied topics prevent discussion of certain subjects; they cannot detect PII within document content.<br>D — There is no Privacy content filter category in Bedrock Guardrails."},
  {d:3,q:"A developer deletes an Aurora Serverless v2 cluster that uses a customer-managed KMS key. What issue arises with automated snapshots?",o:["Snapshots are automatically deleted when the cluster is deleted","Snapshots remain accessible and can be restored immediately","The KMS key enters PendingDeletion (7-30 days), preventing snapshot restoration","Snapshots are migrated to AWS-managed key encryption automatically"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> When you delete a KMS customer-managed key (CMK), it enters PendingDeletion with a 7-30 day waiting period. Automated snapshots encrypted with that key cannot be restored during or after this period. For development clusters, use AWS-managed keys (alias/aws/rds).<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Snapshots are retained according to the backup retention policy, not automatically deleted with the cluster.<br>B — Snapshots encrypted with a deleted CMK cannot be restored.<br>D — AWS does not automatically re-encrypt snapshots with a different key."},
  {d:3,q:"Which IAM permission does a Lambda function need to call the Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases RetrieveAndGenerate API?",o:["bedrock:InvokeModel","bedrock:RetrieveAndGenerate","bedrock:GetKnowledgeBase","bedrock:QueryKnowledgeBase"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> The IAM action required to call RetrieveAndGenerate is <code>bedrock:RetrieveAndGenerate</code>. This is distinct from <code>bedrock:InvokeModel</code> which is required for direct model invocation. Both are typically needed in a full RAG pipeline.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — bedrock:InvokeModel grants permission to call the model directly but does not grant access to the Knowledge Bases RetrieveAndGenerate API.<br>C — bedrock:GetKnowledgeBase is a management permission for viewing Knowledge Base configuration, not querying it.<br>D — bedrock:QueryKnowledgeBase is not a valid IAM action for Bedrock."},
  {d:3,q:"A Lambda function in a private VPC calls Bedrock Knowledge Bases using RetrieveAndGenerate. The function consistently times out. No NAT Gateway. What is the most likely cause?",o:["The Lambda function timeout is too short","The bedrock-agent-runtime VPC interface endpoint is missing","The IAM role lacks bedrock:RetrieveAndGenerate permission","The Knowledge Base sync has not completed"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> RetrieveAndGenerate calls go through the <code>bedrock-agent-runtime</code> service endpoint. Without a VPC interface endpoint for this service, traffic cannot reach Bedrock from a private VPC. The call silently hangs until the Lambda timeout rather than returning an immediate error.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Increasing timeout would just move the failure later; it would not resolve the connectivity issue.<br>C — An IAM permission error returns an AccessDeniedException immediately, not a timeout.<br>D — An unsynced Knowledge Base returns an error response, not a timeout."},
  {d:3,q:"A company wants to enforce that no Amazon Bedrock model except Claude Haiku can be used across all 15 AWS accounts. Which mechanism enforces this at the organisational level?",o:["IAM resource-based policies on Bedrock models","AWS Config rules for Bedrock compliance","Service Control Policies (SCPs) attached to the organisation or OUs","Amazon Bedrock Guardrails applied globally"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Service Control Policies (SCPs) are applied at the AWS Organisations level and restrict what any IAM principal in affected accounts can do — even administrators. An SCP denying bedrock:InvokeModel on all resources except the allowed model ARN enforces model restriction across all accounts.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Resource-based policies are attached to specific AWS resources; Bedrock models do not support resource-based policies from external accounts.<br>B — Config rules detect non-compliance after the fact; they do not prevent non-compliant actions.<br>D — Guardrails apply content filters to model responses; they cannot restrict which models are invoked."},
  {d:3,q:"A company's RAG system sometimes generates plausible answers not supported by the retrieved documents. Which Guardrails feature specifically detects and prevents this?",o:["Content filters set to Maximum for all categories","Denied topics covering unsupported claims","Sensitive information filters","Contextual grounding filter with threshold 0.75"],a:3,e:"<span class='why-correct'>D is correct.</span> The contextual grounding filter is specifically designed to detect hallucination in RAG systems. It measures how well the generated answer is supported by the retrieved context chunks. Answers scoring below the threshold are blocked as potentially hallucinated.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Content filters address hate, violence, sexual content, etc. They cannot determine whether an answer is supported by documents.<br>B — Denied topics prevent discussion of specific subjects; they cannot evaluate grounding of answers against retrieved content.<br>C — Sensitive information filters detect PII; they have no grounding or hallucination detection capability."},
  {d:3,q:"What type of prompt injection attack occurs when malicious instructions are embedded inside retrieved documents rather than in the user's direct query?",o:["Direct prompt injection","Indirect prompt injection","System prompt extraction","Jailbreaking"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Indirect prompt injection embeds attack instructions inside content that the model retrieves and processes — such as a webpage, document, or database record. When the RAG system includes this content in the prompt context, the model may follow the embedded instructions.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Direct prompt injection is when the user themselves types the malicious instructions.<br>C — System prompt extraction is the goal of an attack, not the attack vector itself.<br>D — Jailbreaking involves techniques to bypass model safety training, not specifically through retrieved documents."},
  {d:3,q:"A company wants to mask email and phone numbers in AI responses but completely block any response containing credit card numbers. Which Guardrails configuration is correct?",o:["Set all PII types to Block","Set email and phone to Mask, set credit card to Block","Set all PII types to Mask with threshold 0.9","Use denied topics for credit card data"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Bedrock Guardrails sensitive information filters allow per-PII-type configuration. You can set email and phone to Mask (replacing them with redacted placeholders) while setting credit card numbers to Block (blocking the entire response if detected).<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Blocking all PII types would block any response containing an email or phone number, making many legitimate responses unavailable.<br>C — PII masking does not have a threshold parameter; you configure the action (Mask or Block) per PII type.<br>D — Denied topics are for conversation subjects, not for blocking specific data formats."},
  {d:3,q:"A developer tests their RAG system and receives 'Sorry, the model cannot answer this question' for a legitimate factual query. The Guardrail contextual grounding threshold is 0.75. What is the most likely explanation?",o:["The model does not understand the question","The Lambda function lacks bedrock:ApplyGuardrail permission","The answer generated by the model scored below 0.75 grounded against the retrieved context","The Guardrail denied topic filter matched the query"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> This blocked message is returned when the contextual grounding filter determines the model's answer is insufficiently supported by the retrieved chunks. Common cause: the answer is based on facts only mentioned implicitly in headings or tables rather than in explicit prose sentences. The fix: make facts explicit in the document.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Model comprehension issues don't produce this specific Bedrock blocked message.<br>B — Missing ApplyGuardrail permission would cause an IAM error, not a blocked message from the Guardrail.<br>D — A denied topic match would also produce a blocked response, but contextual grounding failure is more likely for a factual query."},
  {d:3,q:"What is the difference between a hard block and message substitution when a Bedrock Guardrail intervenes?",o:["Hard block returns HTTP 403; substitution returns HTTP 200","Hard block sets stop_reason to guardrail_intervened; substitution returns HTTP 200 with replaced text and stop_reason end_turn","Hard block terminates the Lambda function; substitution adds a warning header","There is no practical difference between the two intervention types"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Hard block: the API response includes <code>stop_reason: guardrail_intervened</code> and <code>amazon-bedrock-guardrailAction</code>. Message substitution: the Guardrail replaces the blocked response with a pre-configured safe message, returning HTTP 200 with <code>stop_reason: end_turn</code> — your code cannot tell it from a normal response without inspecting the content.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Both hard block and substitution can return HTTP 200; the difference is in the response body, not HTTP status code.<br>C — Lambda is not terminated by Guardrail interventions.<br>D — The practical difference is significant: hard block is programmatically detectable; substitution may not be noticed without content inspection."},
  {d:3,q:"Which AWS service provides documentation about AI model behaviour, intended use cases, and limitations to support responsible AI decision-making?",o:["Amazon Bedrock Guardrails","Amazon SageMaker Clarify","AWS AI Service Cards","AWS Config"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> AWS AI Service Cards are documentation artifacts published by AWS that describe the intended use cases, limitations, responsible AI design choices, and performance characteristics of AI services and models.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Guardrails applies runtime safety filters to model inputs and outputs; it is not documentation about model behaviour.<br>B — SageMaker Clarify detects bias and explains model predictions for custom models; it is not the same as AI Service Cards.<br>D — AWS Config monitors resource configuration compliance; it is not related to AI model documentation."},

  // DOMAIN 4 (9 questions)
  {d:4,q:"A startup runs a RAG chatbot with unpredictable traffic — quiet during the day, sometimes busy in the evenings. Which Amazon Bedrock throughput model minimises cost?",o:["Provisioned throughput with reserved capacity","On-demand throughput","Scheduled throughput based on predicted traffic","Spot throughput with interruption handling"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> On-demand throughput charges only for tokens actually processed, with no upfront commitment. For unpredictable or bursty workloads, on-demand is the most cost-effective. Provisioned throughput requires paying for reserved model units regardless of usage.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Provisioned throughput requires a minimum commitment (hourly charges for reserved model units). For variable workloads, you pay for unused capacity during quiet periods.<br>C — There is no scheduled throughput option in Amazon Bedrock.<br>D — There is no spot throughput option in Amazon Bedrock."},
  {d:4,q:"An Aurora Serverless v2 cluster configured with min_capacity=0 has been idle for 45 minutes. A user submits a query. What should the developer expect?",o:["The query returns immediately with no cold start","The query fails permanently with a connection timeout error","The cluster wakes up in 10-20 seconds, causing noticeable latency for the first query","Aurora Serverless v2 does not support min_capacity=0"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> When min_capacity=0, the cluster scales completely to zero after the configured idle period. The first request triggers a warm-up taking approximately 10-20 seconds. Lambda needs retry logic during this period. For latency-sensitive production RAG, set min_capacity=0.5 ACU.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — There is a measurable cold start; scale-to-zero does not provide instant startup.<br>B — The connection does not fail permanently; with retry logic, the connection succeeds after the warm-up period.<br>D — Aurora Serverless v2 does support min_capacity=0 (scale-to-zero) as of PostgreSQL 16.4."},
  {d:4,q:"A team monitoring their Bedrock RAG application wants to detect when model invocations are being throttled. Which CloudWatch metric should they alert on?",o:["InvocationLatency","InputTokenCount","ThrottledRequests","ModelInvocationCount"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> ThrottledRequests counts how many Bedrock API calls were rejected due to exceeding per-account or per-model rate limits. Alerting on this metric helps detect when the application needs backoff logic or provisioned throughput.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — InvocationLatency measures how long model invocations take; high latency can indicate throttling but does not directly measure it.<br>B — InputTokenCount tracks total tokens sent; useful for cost monitoring, not throttling detection.<br>D — ModelInvocationCount is not a standard Bedrock CloudWatch metric name."},
  {d:4,q:"A company runs a high-volume RAG pipeline choosing between Claude Haiku and Claude Sonnet. Haiku meets their quality requirements. Which factor most strongly favours choosing Haiku?",o:["Haiku has a larger context window than Sonnet","Haiku has a significantly lower per-token cost than Sonnet","Haiku supports more programming languages for code generation","Haiku has better multi-step reasoning for complex queries"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> In the Claude model family, Haiku is the smallest and cheapest model with significantly lower per-token costs than Sonnet. For high-volume workloads where quality requirements are met by Haiku, choosing it over Sonnet can reduce inference costs by 4-8x.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Sonnet typically has a larger or equal context window compared to Haiku.<br>C — Both models support code generation; cost is the practical differentiator.<br>D — Sonnet has stronger reasoning capabilities than Haiku — this is an argument for Sonnet, not Haiku."},
  {d:4,q:"A Lambda function fetches a versioned prompt from Bedrock Prompt Management on every invocation, adding 100ms of latency per call. Which Python mechanism eliminates this overhead?",o:["Store the prompt in an environment variable","Use functools.lru_cache to cache the result of the GetPrompt call","Cache the prompt in DynamoDB with a 1-hour TTL","Use a Lambda Layer to include the prompt as a static file"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> <code>@functools.lru_cache(maxsize=1)</code> caches the GetPrompt return value in Lambda's execution environment memory. Subsequent invocations in the same execution environment skip the API call and return the cached prompt instantly. The cache is cleared on cold starts.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Environment variables are set at deployment time; updating them requires redeployment — defeating the purpose of Prompt Management versioning.<br>C — DynamoDB adds a read operation per invocation; still has latency and requires IAM permissions.<br>D — Storing prompts as static files requires redeployment to update."},
  {d:4,q:"What is the primary advantage of using Amazon Bedrock cross-region inference profiles over direct foundation model invocation?",o:["Cross-region profiles cost less per token than direct invocation","Cross-region profiles route requests to the least-loaded region for higher availability and throughput","Cross-region profiles support models not available in the primary region","Cross-region profiles provide lower latency by using the geographically nearest region"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Cross-region inference profiles (eu. or us. prefix) route requests across multiple AWS regions within a geographic area to the region with available capacity. This provides higher throughput limits and better availability than direct single-region invocation.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Cross-region profiles may cost slightly more per token due to cross-region routing overhead.<br>C — Cross-region profiles route to regions where the model is already available; they do not provide access to additional models.<br>D — Cross-region routing may increase latency if the request is routed to a more distant region; lower latency is not the primary benefit."},
  {d:4,q:"A company processes 10 million tokens per day through their RAG pipeline using Claude Haiku and considers upgrading to Claude Sonnet. What is the primary cost consideration?",o:["Sonnet charges per API call rather than per token","Sonnet costs significantly more per token, making the upgrade 4-8x more expensive per million tokens","Both models have identical pricing; the difference is only in quality","Sonnet is cheaper for input tokens but more expensive for output tokens"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Claude Sonnet costs approximately 4-8x more per token than Claude Haiku for both input and output. For a 10 million token per day workload, this difference is significant. Use Bedrock Evaluations to quantify the quality delta before committing to the upgrade.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Bedrock charges per token (input and output separately), not per API call.<br>C — Haiku and Sonnet have substantially different per-token pricing.<br>D — Both input and output token costs differ between Haiku and Sonnet."},
  {d:4,q:"An Aurora Serverless v2 cluster with min_capacity=0 is experiencing high latency on the first query of each morning. The team wants to eliminate cold start without overspending. What is the best solution?",o:["Increase max_capacity from 2 to 8 ACU","Set min_capacity to 0.5 ACU to keep the cluster warm at low cost","Switch to Aurora Serverless v1 for better cold start performance","Add a cron Lambda that queries the database every 5 minutes"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Setting min_capacity=0.5 ACU keeps a small baseline capacity running at all times, eliminating the cold start delay. At 0.5 ACU the cost is approximately £0.06-0.10 per hour — much less than a full RDS instance. This is the AWS-recommended production configuration for latency-sensitive RAG.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — max_capacity controls the peak scaling limit, not the idle floor. It does not affect cold start behaviour.<br>C — Aurora Serverless v1 has longer cold starts than v2 and is being deprecated.<br>D — A keepalive Lambda works but is a workaround; setting min_capacity is the cleaner, AWS-recommended solution."},
  {d:4,q:"A company wants to reduce Bedrock costs for a RAG chatbot where users often ask semantically similar questions. Which optimisation strategy most directly reduces model invocations?",o:["Reduce the max_tokens parameter to limit response length","Implement semantic caching to serve cached answers for similar questions","Use provisioned throughput for lower per-token cost","Reduce the top_k retrieval parameter to speed up queries"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Semantic caching stores question-answer pairs as vectors. When a new question arrives, it is compared against cached questions using cosine similarity. If similarity exceeds a threshold, the cached answer is returned without calling the model at all — eliminating 30-60% of model invocations for typical chatbot workloads.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Reducing max_tokens reduces output length and cost per generation but does not reduce the number of model invocations.<br>C — Provisioned throughput lowers per-token cost for high-volume workloads but does not reduce model invocations.<br>D — Reducing top_k reduces retrieval cost slightly but does not skip model invocations."},

  // DOMAIN 5 (8 questions)
  {d:5,q:"A team wants to evaluate whether their RAG system generates high-quality answers using an automated approach that does not require human annotation. Which Bedrock evaluation method is most appropriate?",o:["Human evaluation using an internal workforce","Programmatic evaluation using ROUGE and BERTScore metrics","Automatic model evaluation using LLM-as-judge with Claude Sonnet as the judge","A/B testing with live users over 30 days"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Automatic model evaluation using LLM-as-judge uses a strong model (Claude Sonnet) to evaluate the outputs of a weaker model (Claude Haiku) against reference answers. It assesses Faithfulness, Correctness, Completeness, and Relevance — qualities that string-matching metrics cannot measure.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Human evaluation produces high-quality assessments but is slow, expensive, and not scalable.<br>B — ROUGE and BERTScore are string-matching metrics. They penalise semantically correct answers with different wording — not suitable for open-ended Q&A.<br>D — A/B testing has a 30-day delay, exposes users to potentially lower-quality responses, and requires significant traffic."},
  {d:5,q:"A developer uses ROUGE-L scores to evaluate their RAG system. Scores are consistently low, but human reviewers rate the answers as accurate and helpful. What explains this discrepancy?",o:["The RAG system is hallucinating but humans are not catching it","ROUGE-L penalises semantically correct answers that use different vocabulary from the reference","The human reviewers are not qualified to assess answer quality","ROUGE-L is not a valid metric for evaluating AI-generated text"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> ROUGE measures lexical overlap — how many words or n-grams from the reference answer appear in the generated answer. A semantically correct answer that paraphrases rather than reproduces the reference will score poorly. LLM-as-judge evaluation is more appropriate for open-ended RAG Q&A.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — If humans rate answers as accurate, hallucination is unlikely; the more probable explanation is a metric limitation.<br>C — Human expert reviewers provide valuable signal; ROUGE's inability to detect semantic correctness is the issue here.<br>D — ROUGE is a valid metric but is best suited for tasks with near-verbatim expected outputs."},
  {d:5,q:"In Amazon Bedrock Evaluations, which metric specifically measures whether the generated answer is supported by the retrieved context documents?",o:["Correctness","Relevance","Completeness","Faithfulness"],a:3,e:"<span class='why-correct'>D is correct.</span> Faithfulness measures whether each claim in the generated answer is grounded in the retrieved context. A faithfulness score near 1.0 means the model only stated things supported by the retrieved chunks. A low score indicates hallucination.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Correctness measures factual accuracy by comparing the answer against a reference answer; it can score a hallucinated answer as correct if the hallucination happens to be factually right.<br>B — Relevance measures whether the answer is on-topic; it does not measure grounding in context.<br>C — Completeness measures whether the answer fully addresses all aspects of the question; it does not measure grounding."},
  {d:5,q:"A team uses Amazon Bedrock Evaluations with Claude Sonnet as the judge and Claude Haiku as the evaluated model. Why must the judge model be stronger?",o:["AWS requires the judge to be more expensive for billing purposes","A weaker judge cannot reliably assess quality or identify errors in responses","A stronger judge can more reliably identify quality issues, errors, and hallucinations in the evaluated model's responses","The judge needs more compute resources to process evaluation metrics"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> In LLM-as-judge evaluation, the judge needs sufficient intelligence to critically evaluate answers, detect subtle errors, and assess quality accurately. If the judge is weaker or equal to the evaluated model, it may not identify mistakes. Sonnet judging Haiku is appropriate because Sonnet is a stronger model.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Model selection for evaluation is based on capability, not billing requirements.<br>B — This partially describes the principle but is less precise than C.<br>D — Compute resources do not determine model selection for evaluation; reasoning capability does."},
  {d:5,q:"What file format and required fields does Amazon Bedrock Evaluations expect for the evaluation dataset?",o:["CSV with question, answer, and category columns","JSON array with question and referenceResponse objects","JSONL with prompt, referenceResponse, and category fields per line","XML with structured EvaluationRecord elements"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Amazon Bedrock Evaluations requires a JSONL (JSON Lines) file where each line is a JSON object containing: <code>prompt</code> (the question), <code>referenceResponse</code> (the ground-truth answer), and <code>category</code> (question type such as 'question_answering').<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Bedrock Evaluations does not accept CSV format.<br>B — A JSON array would be missing the required category field and would not be in JSONL format.<br>D — XML is not supported as an evaluation dataset format by Amazon Bedrock Evaluations."},
  {d:5,q:"A developer stores their evaluation dataset (eval-dataset.jsonl) under the docs/ prefix in their RAG S3 bucket. After uploading the eval file, the RAG system starts returning strange answers. What happened?",o:["The eval dataset corrupted the pgvector index","The S3 event notification triggered the Ingest Lambda on the eval file, embedding eval Q&A pairs into the vector store","The Bedrock Knowledge Base synced the eval file as a new document","The eval file overwrote one of the source documents"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> The S3 event notification was configured to trigger the Ingest Lambda on all object creates under <code>docs/</code>. Uploading the eval JSONL to that prefix triggered ingestion of the eval Q&A pairs as if they were documents, contaminating retrieval results. The fix: store eval data under a separate prefix (e.g., evals/) and configure the event notification filter accordingly.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — S3 uploads cannot directly corrupt a pgvector index; the issue is through the ingestion pipeline.<br>C — The Knowledge Base sync includes the eval file only if its S3 URI matches the Knowledge Base data source path.<br>D — S3 puts objects at new keys; the eval file would not overwrite existing documents unless it used the exact same S3 key."},
  {d:5,q:"A developer wants to compare two system prompt versions for their RAG chatbot and determine which produces higher faithfulness and correctness scores. Which approach should they use?",o:["Bedrock Evaluations with A/B test configuration","Bedrock Knowledge Bases with multiple data sources","Run two Bedrock Evaluations jobs — one with each prompt ARN — and compare the scores","Bedrock Guardrails threshold comparison"],a:2,e:"<span class='why-correct'>C is correct.</span> Create two versions of the prompt in Bedrock Prompt Management (version 1 and version 2). Run two Bedrock Evaluations jobs — one with each prompt version ARN — against the same evaluation dataset. Compare the faithfulness, correctness, completeness, and relevance scores to determine which prompt performs better.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Bedrock Evaluations does not have a built-in A/B test configuration that runs two prompts simultaneously in one job.<br>B — Knowledge Bases data sources control document retrieval, not prompt selection.<br>D — Guardrail thresholds control safety filtering, not prompt quality comparison."},
  {d:5,q:"A RAG system returns confident, well-written answers that contain factual errors. The retrieved documents also contain those same factual errors. Which evaluation metric would score HIGH despite the incorrect facts?",o:["Correctness","Faithfulness","Completeness","Relevance"],a:1,e:"<span class='why-correct'>B is correct.</span> Faithfulness only measures whether the answer is grounded in the retrieved context — it does not check whether the context itself is factually correct. If the retrieved chunks contain wrong information and the model faithfully reproduces it, the Faithfulness score will be high. Correctness, by contrast, compares against a reference answer and would detect the factual error.<br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong><br>A — Correctness compares the generated answer against a reference (ground-truth) answer. It would score LOW because the answer contains factual errors.<br>C — Completeness measures whether all parts of the question were addressed, not factual accuracy.<br>D — Relevance measures whether the answer is on-topic, not whether it is factually correct."}
];
